## 2. How To Localize A Failure

When the symptom is not in the table, localize before guessing:

1. Reproduce the symptom on a fixed input and a fixed seed, so the failure is stable enough to study.
2. Confirm what actually changed since the last good {{EXPERIMENT_UNIT_LABEL}} by reading `docs/evaluation/comparison.md`; a symptom that seems to point at two components usually means more than one thing changed.
3. Bisect along the data flow in `docs/method/method-overview.md` section 1: inspect the intermediate output between two components and ask which side looks wrong. Repeat on the wrong side.
4. Apply the cheapest discriminating check first; prefer a check that rules out a whole component over one that inspects a single value.
5. Once localized, either fix it or, if the change itself is the cause and unfixable, record the verdict and add a row to `docs/method/algorithmic-levers.md` section 3.

Common pitfall: changing two things to "fix it faster" destroys attribution. Change one thing, re-check, repeat, exactly as in a normal {{EXPERIMENT_UNIT_LABEL}}.
